etymologies: early 19th century; earliest use found in Samuel Taylor Coleridge (1772–1834), poet, critic, and philosopher. From case + -less

definitions: That has no case; morphologically unmarked; uninflected.
Characterized by a lack of court cases; (of a lawyer) without a case to work on, idle.

etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in Richmond (Indiana) Palladium. From case + -less

definitions: Not enclosed in or having a case; (especially of a clock or other manufactured object) lacking an outer protective or covering case.
Of ammunition: that does not have or need a cartridge to hold charge and bullet together; (of a firearm) using such ammunition.
